# Memory management in incant

## The problem every language has to solve

Every time a program creates something — a string, a list, a data structure — it needs memory to store it. And when that thing is no longer needed, the memory should be reclaimed so it can be used for something else.

In older languages like C, the programmer handles this manually: you ask for memory, you use it, you free it. This is fast and precise, but it's also a rich source of bugs. Free memory too early and you have a pointer to something that no longer exists — a crash waiting to happen. Forget to free it and you have a *memory leak* — the program slowly consumes more and more memory until it runs out or is restarted.

Modern languages solve this differently. Most use *garbage collection*: the runtime tracks which objects are still reachable and periodically reclaims the ones that aren't. The programmer doesn't think about memory — the language takes care of it.

## What incant uses

incant uses the Boehm-Demers-Weiser garbage collector, known as BDWGC. It's a mature, well-tested library that has been in production use for decades, embedded in everything from GCC to Mono to game engines.

BDWGC is a *conservative* collector. That means it doesn't require the program to tell it exactly where all the pointers are — instead, it scans memory and treats anything that *looks like* a pointer as one. If a value in memory could be a valid address of a live object, the collector assumes it is and keeps that object alive. This conservative approach trades a small amount of precision (a handful of objects might be kept alive slightly longer than strictly necessary) for a large amount of simplicity: BDWGC works with ordinary C++ code without requiring special pointer registration or annotation.

## Why it matters for incant

incant's core data structure — the GroupItem — is allocated and used constantly as programs run. Rules parse input, actions execute, expressions evaluate: all of this creates GroupItems, links them together, and eventually stops referring to them. Without a garbage collector, all of that would require careful manual management in the C++ kernel — a significant source of complexity and bugs.

With BDWGC, GroupItems that are no longer reachable (no other live object holds a reference to them) are collected automatically. The incant runtime allocates freely and trusts the collector to clean up.

## What this means in practice

For someone writing incant programs, memory management is invisible — which is the point. You create fields, build lists, run actions, and don't think about memory.

For the incant runtime and JIT, there's one detail worth understanding: BDWGC scans the stack and global memory for pointers. As long as a pointer to an object exists somewhere the scanner can reach, that object stays alive. The JIT relies on this: when compiled code bakes in the address of an incant object, the object stays alive because it remains rooted in the live incant object graph; while compiled code is executing, its baked addresses are also live in registers and on the stack, which the collector scans — so an object in use can't be collected mid-flight. (An object referenced *only* by a baked address in idle compiled code is not protected — it must be reachable some other way.)

The choice of BDWGC reflects the pragmatic design philosophy running through incant: use proven, industrial-strength infrastructure for the hard problems (LLVM for JIT compilation, BDWGC for memory management) and focus incant's own engineering effort on what's unique to the language.

## GUI work makes this especially visible

Graphical interfaces are particularly demanding on memory management. Every user interaction — a button click, a menu opening, a list scrolling past, a form field updating — creates a small flurry of objects: layout structures, event records, temporary display values. Most of them are needed for a fraction of a second and then serve no further purpose.

In a language without garbage collection, tracking and freeing all of those short-lived objects would be a significant burden — and getting it wrong would mean either crashes (freeing something too early) or the program slowly consuming more and more memory over a long session until it becomes sluggish or dies.

With BDWGC, incant's GUI work simply creates what it needs. The collector runs periodically in the background, finds all the objects that are no longer reachable, and reclaims them. A long interactive session stays as lean as a short one. This isn't a nice-to-have in GUI work — it's what makes building GUIs in incant practical at all.
